comment: The only good thing about this is the clear victim biasness we face in this society. I will not listen to another person promoting women's rights until both of our plights are acknowledged equally. I remember being physically attacked on my school bus by two girls in middle school. I was left with dozens of scratch marks and a bruise on my chin. I got so mad that I punched one of them in the knee and I immediately became the bad guy. The bus driver threatened to suspend me and a couple of other girls called me some names. Another incident I faced in my youth was a girl threatening to beat me up if I didn't date her friend. Chances are you wont believe this story, but that is the point I'm trying to make; men and women do not have equality. I don't resent women, but their attitudes need to change about who can labeled as a victim of domestic violence. I know men are more than capable of defending ourselves, but everytime we defend ourselves we are immediately assumed to be the aggressor. Men need to support women and women need to support men if we want to strive for equality.
